@Kat | Biττensor CM・won't DM 1st Assuming I generated the seed phrase on the bittensor.wallet platform and stored it offline (on paper) , what are some of the possible attack vectors that would cause me to be hacked?

The only one I can think of off the top of my head is that if you leave yourself connected (e.g., via cookies through your browser), and someone gains access to your computer or tricks you into granting remote access (through, say, AnyDesk or some other RAT), they could access your account that way.   For the Bittensor wallet, they're also going to need your password, of course, but this is going to be a vulnerability of any hot wallet.

When you generate your seed phrase on Bittensor, though, it's not stored anywhere on the server side.  I don't know the exact technical process of how data goes back and forth, but it's not sent unencrypted, and the server doesn't retain the phrase.  This is why we can't help folks who've lost their seed phrase; we have no access to it in any shape or form (and anyone claiming otherwise and trying to trick you into "confirming" it is a scammer).

Hopefully one of the more knowledgable folks will jump in here, but from my personal perspective, the Bittensor wallet is just fine.  But I am not super hard-core security focused, so this answer may be completely unsatisfactory for someone like that -- as always, your mileage may vary.

Oh!  Also, I believe that if you generate your wallet using btcli, the whole process is constrained to your computer/wherever btcli is running, and the seed is absolutely not stored (which is why it warns you to write it down).  You could disconnect your computer from the Internet, set up the wallet, and then reconnect it, and your seed phrase would never be exposed (except to your eyeballs, and Van Eyk phreakers, but just don't do this while sitting in a prison in the Philippines when the authorities have unexplicably allowed you access to your personal laptop but restricted you to using it on a suspiciously heavy and locked filing cabinet as a table\* -- or of course the more prosaic possibility of someone having installed keylogging malware on your computer)

The main difference is that the verified validators are publicly listed, and you know who they are and what they're doing, so if the work of their operators is something that means something to you, you know where the 18% fee that they're earning from your stake is likely going to. : )

When you delegate to a validator, the validator is using your Tao to earn additional rewards and increase its position on the network, but the validator does not have access to your staked Tao and cannot take them, even if operating maliciously: your Tao is never forfeited nor are the additional gains you receive in the form of Tao at a rate of 82% of that validator’s rate. 

If the validator goes down, both you and the validator stop earning Tao. At that point, you can unstake your Tao (including any gains you earned while validator was running) and the validator keeps their portion of the additional gains from your your Tao (18%).  Your original stake and rewards earned are never in jeopardy and can be unstaked at any time.
